#week-title("Four", "The Stone as Symbol of the Completed Human Being")

=== Core Teaching

The tradition offers one further interpretation of the Stone that, at the
Adept level and in the final quarter of the curriculum, becomes most
practically relevant: the Stone as a symbol of the completed human being.

The Philosopher's Stone in the fullest sense is not merely a substance that
projects virtue upon metals. It is the symbol and the reality of what a human
being becomes who has genuinely undergone the Great Work — whose three
principles have been separated, purified, and reunited at a level higher than
the ordinary confused mixture in which most human beings live.

Such a practitioner:
- Has a Sulphur (soul) that is genuinely characteristic — specific, essential,
  no longer mixed with inherited persona and social performance.
- Has a Mercury (spirit) that is genuinely connective — able to hold complexity,
  to perceive subtle relationships, to be present without projecting.
- Has a Salt (body and habit) that is genuinely structured — the fixed principle
  in service of the soul and spirit, not a cage constraining them.

And such a practitioner *projects* — not by intention or technique, but by
presence. Those who come into sustained contact with a genuinely developed
practitioner find themselves drawn toward their own highest nature. This is the
Stone's projection in the human kingdom: not a chemical act but a quality of
presence that the Work has built.

This is the interpretation that answers the question: why do the work at all?
The Stone is not primarily for making gold — it is for becoming the kind of being
through whom the highest human potential naturally expresses itself.

*Preparation for Quarter IV.* The student assembles the final presentation:
the complete three-year Work; the alchemical journal passage to be read aloud;
the declaration of ongoing practice; the letter to a future Tyro.

=== Topics This Week

- The Stone as symbol and reality of the completed human being
- The projection in the human kingdom: presence that draws others to their highest
- Westcott's reconciliation at the Human level: the practitioner as the Cosmic's
  instrument
- Preparation for Year Three Quarter IV Gathering and commencement

#inner-work[
  *The Completed Human Being*

  This is not an exercise in self-congratulation. Read what the tradition says
  about the completed practitioner: Albertus in Chapter VII, Case on Key 21
  (The World), Westcott's Human level, Canseliet on the practitioner who has
  doffed ego-mortality.

  Then write one paragraph, honestly: how far are you from this description?
  Not as self-criticism — as navigation. The practitioner who knows clearly
  where they stand has the most direct path forward.
]

